High-speed internet access via smartphones could become a feature on European airline flights following a deal involving the German carrier Lufthansa -- but voice calls will be blocked at first. Lufthansa will offer Wi-Fi on its short - and medium-haul flights from 2017, provided by the satellite firm Inmarsat and Deutsche Telekom. The companies claim their venture, which combines ground-based mobile broadband networks and the nascent satellite networks already used on some planes, will permit a more reliable, faster connection than passengers currently experience. However, the prospect of high-speed internet access to facilitate communication in the sky has not been universally welcomed. However, the prospect of high-speed internet access to facilitate communication in the sky has not been universally welcomed. However, the prospect of high-speed internet access to facilitate communication in the sky has not been universally welcomed. 
